---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'The report — Dual-marker discovery';
const description =
  'Patient-robust discovery of combinatorial cell-surface targets in prostate cancer. The full scientific report: methods, results, robustness, and limitations.';
---
<Base title={title} description={description} page="report">
  <section class="hero" style="padding-bottom:0.6rem">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The science</p>
      <h1>The report</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Patient-robust discovery of combinatorial cell-surface targets in prostate cancer. Abstract,
        background, data, methods, results, robustness, and limitations. Every number in it is read from
        a committed table, and the report redraws its own figures from those tables with no network call
        and no model call.
      </p>
      <div class="embed-bar">
        <a class="btn primary" href="/report.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open the report in a new tab &rarr;</a>
        <span class="pill">Revised twice under adversarial review</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <p>
          Read the limitations. They are not boilerplate: the malignant label is the cohort authors' own
          signature call and partly overlaps the panel being scored, the healthy reference is restricted
          to a single assay chemistry, the coverage floor's confidence interval is wide, and the NOT gate
          returned nothing. All of that is in there, stated by the report rather than discovered by you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="block">
    <div class="container">
      <iframe class="embed" src="/report.html" title="Scientific report" loading="lazy"></iframe>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
